# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1883-philadelphia-athletics-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-philadelphia-athletics-season] The 1882 season was the first season for the brand new **Philadelphia Athletics** (no relation, except by name, to the previous Philadelphia Athletics team).
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1882-philadelphia-athletics-season] They finished with a 41–34 record and a third-place position in the brand new American Association league.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1883 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 13th season of the franchise.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-boston-beaneaters-season] The Beaneaters won their third National League pennant, their third in six years.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-boston-beaneaters-season] This is also generally recognized as the year during which the team's nickname became the **Boston Beaneaters**.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-buffalo-bisons-season] The **1883 Buffalo Bisons** finished the season with a 52–45 record, good for fifth place in the National League.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-buffalo-bisons-season] Star slugger Dan Brouthers won his second consecutive NL batting title with a .374 average and Pud Galvin posted 46 wins.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1883 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 12th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the eighth in the National League and the sixth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished second in the National League with a record of 59–39.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1883 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished third in the American Association with a record of 61–37, 5 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings came into the 1883 season looking to repeat as American Association Champions, as they had a league best record of 55–25 in 1882.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the team announced that catcher Pop Snyder would return as player-manager.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also made a big signing, as they signed Charley Jones, who played with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League from 1876–1878.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Jones had not played professional baseball since 1880, when he played for the Boston Red Caps of the NL, after which he was black-balled from professional baseball.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings also signed another former Reds player, John Reilly, who had also last played major league baseball for the Reds in the 1880 season.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the diamond, the Red Stockings were led by Jones, who hit .294 with a team leading ten home runs, as well as a league leading 80 RBI.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Reilly hit a team high .311 with nine homers and 79 RBI.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Will White continued to be the ace of the pitching staff, posting a 43–22 record with 64 complete games and a 2.09 ERA in 577 innings pitched.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started off the season on the right foot, winning their first four games, and had an impressive 11–5 record in their first sixteen ballgames.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they were 3.5 games behind the Athletics.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would continue to play good baseball, and had a 31–23 record.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would then go on to win twelve of their next thirteen games to improve to 43–24.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they only moved up to third place.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would remain in third place for the rest of the season, finishing the year at 61–37, five games behind the Athletics.
[src:1883-philadelphia-athletics-season/1883-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1883 Philadelphia Athletics** finished with a 66–32 record and won the championship of the American Association.
